Thus, my skin had become very tan and my friend called me CHOCOLATE. In high school, my friend liked to call me \u201cCHOCO\u201d or \u201cJOCOBI\u201d because the pronunciation was similar with \u201cCHOCOLATE\u201d in Chinese, and it sounded more adorable and unique. It is funny that everyone knows my nickname instead of my real name, Yi-Chun.\"\n\nWhat has been your favorite thing about the United States so far?\n\"I took a roadtrip with my friends for 2 weeks across 8 states. We went to Everglades National Park in Florida, and it was my first time to make friends with gators. We rowed a rental kayak to look at gators very closely. During the tour, we saw a gator swimming beside our kayak. It was so close that the gator could even open his mouth swallowing us. It was really scary but interesting. All in all, I can have a lot of adventurous activities I've never done in Taiwan.\"\n\nWhat advice would you give to a new student?\n\"I think ELI is a good place to learn English. If you are a basic level English learner, the class is really helpful to picking up all kinds of skill, like listening, reading, and grammar. If you are a medium level English learner, all you need is to practice more and more. Student workers and faculty are the best practice partners. The best way to learn English is getting involved in the English-only environment. You don't need to be afraid of making mistakes when speaking English because everybody is an English learner here. You have to be confident and open your mind to talk to everyone with a smile. Since you are here, enjoy your learning everyday!\"", "type": "photo", "id": "156171931075983_749761748383662", "status_type": "added_photos", "icon": "https://fbstatic-a.akamaihd.net/rsrc.php/v2/yz/r/StEh3RhPvjk.gif"}

We have been informed that international students here at Texas A&M University have been affected by these scams. ISS would like to remind students to be cautious when they are contacted by someone claiming to be from USCIS, DHS, or other such entities by phone.  U.S. Government offices will NOT contact you by phone asking for money, bank information, credit card information, social security numbers, or other personal information. \n\nThese scammers can be very savvy and even intimidating; they may threaten you with deportation, or other types of incarceration. Please do not allow yourself to be unsettled by the scammer\u2019s threats.  If you are contacted by someone stating that they represent a U.S. Government office or law enforcement please ask for their name, their badge number (if they claim to be an officer), and a phone number.  Do not give them any personal or financial information over the phone.   ISS advises you to also look at your caller ID and to write that number down as well.  If you are contacted by such a scammer do not attempt to address this alone, please come to the ISS Office, so that we can assist you. \n\n Sincerely,\n International Student Services"}

Read about Zaid's experience and feel free to share about your own experience with culture shock in the comments below.\n------------------------------------------------------------\n>What is culture shock?: \"The first impressions and initial reactions when a person is involved [in] a new environment.\"\n\n>How does culture shock feel?: \"Terrible. I wondered if I should return home or continue my life here in the United States. I was the genius boy in my country, but when I came here I started making so many mistakes in culture and English. I thought that it's better to be the smart boy in Saudi Arabia than the idiot in the United States.  But after time, I got over culture shock and I was fine.\"\n\n>What is one difference between the U.S. culture and your home country?: \"Here people live individual lives.  In contrast, people in Saudi Arabia live social lives.  Here you build your society.  In Saudi Arabia your society is [inherited from] your father.\"\n\n>What was your funniest English/culture mistake?: \"My second week in the United States, I went to the health center.  While the lady was giving me a shot, I told her 'Pray to me.' The nurse was surprised like, 'What?!'  I said, 'Pray to me.' For a moment, she was shocked and she was staring at me.  She asked, 'Do you mean pray FOR me?' I said, 'Yeah, wish me luck.' She looked relieved and said, 'Alright. You should say pray FOR me.' I was wondering what's the difference between 'to' and 'for.' My friends laughed and told me I was acting like her lord or god, so that's really bad.'\n\n>How did that make you feel?: \"I felt like I have to be very involved in American culture if I want to understand everything.\"\n\n>What is your advice to new students in regard to culture shock?: \"Everyone should decide which differences they will just deal with and which ones they will enjoy.  Everyone will experience culture shock.  It's fine.  It's normal. A former Aggie accidentally meets a former ELI student (with excellend English) on her vacation in Thailand.  (Yes, it's long, but be sure to read to the bottom.)\r\n\r\nHi,\r\n \r\nI am an A&M grad, class of 2002, born and bred in Texas. I was thinking tonight about a trip I took to Thailand, and I thought you may enjoy the story, since yall made part of our Thailand trip possible, in a way!  \r\n \r\nIn 2011, a friend and I were trying to plan our fall trip to Thailand to coincide with the Thai festival Yi Peng.  The festival is for locals, so the government does not go out of its way to help tourists plan for it, and most of the information was in Thai - if you could even find it on the Thai websites.  I wasn't even sure how we would get to the right place for the festival, since it was out of town and (it turned out) down a dirt road quite a ways.  [That's when I met Jack] - I found glowing reviews of his touring services on TripAdvisor, including from tourists that he had escorted to the Yi Peng festival the previous year.  I contacted him, and he helped me with information about the right dates and we arranged for him to escort us to the festival that year, as part of a larger group of tourists he coordinated to escort.  \r\n \r\nJack, his sister, and other family members got us to Yi Peng in vans early, and then we had several hours to wait in a field for the festival to [begin] after dusk.  While we waited, Jack came over to Monica and me, to chat and pass the time.  He asked us where we were from - we told him Texas (though I now live in New York), and he said \"Texas!  Howdy!  Dallas, Houston, College Station!\"  Monica and I looked at each other - there we were in a field outside of Chiang Mai, Thailand and this friendly tour guide we found on the internet knew both \"Howdy\" and about College Station!  \r\n\r\nVery quickly we found out that Jack had come to Texas A&M from Thailand to learn English - and that all of us had been there at the same time in 1998!  He called his sister over, since she had also learned English [at the ELI] around the same time, and we had a fun discussion about their experiences in Texas, and about our travel plans for Thailand.  Jack told us about his flight to Houston from Thailand, and how he, knowing zero English at that point, somehow accidentally boarded a flight from Houston to Baton Rouge, rather than to College Station!  Once he landed in Louisiana, apparently they got him straightened out and he found his way on to College Station.  \r\n \r\nThey had great things to say about their experiences at [the ELI], and their English was fantastic.  I was impressed that they had flown across the world to College Station, learned a language, and made a business out of it in their hometown, giving tailored tours to English-speakers in northern Thailand.  \r\n\r\nWhen I was at A&M, my world was still very small and it was a few years after graduating before I ever went abroad.  I'm making up for lost time now, and I am grateful that A&M [and the ELI] made it possible for me to meet Jack and experience Yi Peng.  The whole day was perfection - and meeting a couple of Thai Aggies was the icing on the cake!  I'm attaching a picture I took that night of the lanterns.  It was absolutely magical.  \r\n \r\nBest,\r\nJulie Martin\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBy the way, Jack is still a tourguide and photographer in Thailand. You can see some of his photos on his facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/#!/jacktamrong.  Be sure to visit him if you're ever in Chiangmai, Thailand.", "type": "photo", "id": "156171931075983_666274380065733", "status_type": "added_photos", "icon": "https://fbstatic-a.akamaihd.net/rsrc.php/v2/yz/r/StEh3RhPvjk.gif"}

Globalization is a main trend and I want to make friends from all over the world.  Actually, it was a dream of mine to come here, and I wanted to fulfill it. And I made friends from all over the world.\"\r\n\r\n*What has been the most difficult part of studying at the ELI?  \"It was a big challenge to come here because I never stayed in another country for a long time.  But I'm very happy here.  I'm also very sad that I am going to leave.  I'll miss my friends because they stretch my thinking.\"\r\n\r\n*What's next for you? \"I'm going to Japan to be a part-time farmer before I go to find another job.  After that, I will start my new life- maybe in Taiwan, or maybe in Hong Kong or Singapore.\"\r\n\r\n*What's an interesting fact about you?  \"I could read Chinese characters from the time I was one year old. I am glad to hear that. I've been studying at the ELI since last semester. As I'm your upperclassman, I hope to give you some precious advice of what I experienced firsthand that can guide you to learn in more effective way. I'm quite sorry that I will have gone back to my country when you come here, so we can't talk face to face. Nevertheless, you can read it and bear these thoughts in your mind.\r\n\r\nFirst of all, submit your assignments on time. As a student, submitting homework on time is mandatory. If you are late you will get 8 points subtracted per day. It will directly affect your final score. If your final score is under 80, you have to repeat the same class another semester. I thought teachers would let all of the students pass all their classes. However, I saw that a lot of students hadn't passed some classes last semester and now they are taking the same classes from last semester. If you are hungry for more knowledge, don't you think passing the classes are definite and basic elements for satisfying yourself? \r\n\r\nMoreover, keep in mind that you should never use any other language besides English. You should reflect on why you are coming here. As ELI has a lot of students from a great number of countries, you will face numerous foreign students. Endeavor to keep a conversation with them no matter how well you speak English. Don't be shy nor be depressed by making mistakes. The more you speak, the more confidence and fluency you will obtain. We have a lot of American staff in ELI, and whenever you are not sure about grammar or pronunciation, you can ask them as they are available to talk. \r\n\r\nIn addition, go the REC center and make American friends. Studying is important but our health is as significant as studying. Without health what can we do? In Texas A&M we have a fabulous student sport center called the REC. It is the best amenity I've ever seen in Texas A&M. If you have the student identification card you can use it to enter the REC. In the REC you can not only play sports but also can make American friends. I've met two American friends in the REC whom I still connect and play sports with. We quickly became best friends. We've been hanging out together since our first encounter. We've gone to parties and studied this semester. I have also learned real American culture from them and made an incredible improvement in English. I hadn't thought I would make such a satisfied improvement before I came here. Don't always identify yourself as a foreigner. \r\n\r\nTo conclude, I hope you do about which I wrote. Even though we haven't met before, I just hope you enjoy your ELI life and use your leisure time in the most effective way. Submit your assignments on time, never use any other language besides English and \"Go REC\". Playing sports with Americans and being friends with them are kinds of essential requirements for improving your English. In Asia, there is a priceless adage, \"The clever people are not better than those who trouble themselves with studying hard. Those who study hard are not better than those who enjoy what they are studying.\" Enjoy your ELI life and reach your goals.\r\n\r\nSee more essays by ELI students on Mrs. Payne's Composition 250 blog: http://studentwritingtamueli.blogspot.com/2013/03/advice-from-upperclassman.html", "type": "photo", "id": "156171931075983_635431343150037", "status_type": "added_photos", "icon": "https://fbstatic-a.akamaihd.net/rsrc.php/v2/yz/r/StEh3RhPvjk.gif"}
